The Architecture of Django
         Django is a high-level Python web framework engineered to build secure,
         scalable, and data-driven web applications rapidly. It provides a robust structural
         skeleton for backend development. Instead of writing repetitive code to handle database
         connections, user authentication, and security protocols from scratch, a developer utilizes
         Django's built-in tools to manage these complex operations.

         The framework is used extensively in the professional industry to construct backend
         systems that require heavy database interactions. Platforms such as Instagram, Spotify,
         and Pinterest have historically relied on Django to manage massive amounts of data and user traffic securely.

Genesis: System Installation and Generation

        The foundation of this system was constructed through a series of terminal commands.
        First, the Django framework was installed onto the local machine using Python's package
        manager with the command: pip install django.

        Next, the master project container, which acts as the global configuration hub,
        was generated using the command: django-admin startproject mysite.

        To ensure the codebase remained organized and modular, a specialized application
        dedicated solely to view menu items was created inside the project folder using the command:
        python manage.py startapp restaurant_menu.

        Finally, the system's database was initialized by translating the Python code into database tables
        using the commands python manage.py makemigrations followed by python manage.py migrate.

The Structural Blueprint: File Tree Breakdown

        The first visual representation of the project displays the structural hierarchy of the application.
        Every folder and file has a strict, mechanical purpose.

    The Application Directory (restaurant_menu)

        This folder is a modular component designed to perform the specific task of processing
        restaurant_menu submissions.
        migrations Directory: This folder acts as a historical ledger. The file 0001_initial.py
        contains the exact, machine-readable instructions that Django used to construct the database
        tables for the first time.
        templates Directory: This folder contains the visual interface. It holds the HTML files
        (about.html, base.html, menu_item_detail.html, index.html) that are sent to the user's web browser.

    The Configuration Directory (mysite)

        This folder acts as the brain of the entire project, holding the global settings
        that govern how the application behaves.

    __init__.py: A blank file that simply tells Python to treat this directory as a proper software package.

    settings.py: The master control panel.

    urls.py: The global routing map.

    wsgi.py and asgi.py: Server communication files used later when the application is deployed to a live internet server.

The Root Level Files

    db.sqlite3: The physical, local SQL database file where all submitted job applications are permanently stored.

    manage.py: The command-line utility. This file is never edited manually; it is used exclusively in the terminal
                to start the server or execute database updates.

    The Codebase: File Logic and Execution

    The internal code dictates exactly how the system operates when a user interacts with it.

The Core Configuration (settings.py & Project urls.py)

    Inside settings.py, the job_application module is explicitly registered within the INSTALLED_APPS list
    so the framework knows it exists. This file also contains the SMTP configuration
    (EMAIL_BACKEND, EMAIL_HOST, EMAIL_PORT) required to send automated confirmation emails.

    The project-level urls.py file acts as the primary switchboard.
    The code written here explicitly instructs the system to forward any incoming web traffic directly
    to the restaurant_menu's internal routing map.

    The Database Architecture (models.py)

        This file acts as the database architect. The code defines a class named Item that establishes
        the exact blueprint for the database table. It dictates that the system must permanently store a
        meal, description, price, meal_type for every single submission.


    The Operational Logic (views.py)

        This file is the operational brain of the request-and-response cycle.
        It has classes to extract items form html files and helps in building a path for items.

    The Routing Map (urls.py - App Level)

        This file is the local directory. The code connects specific web addresses
        (like the home page, the about page) directly to their
        corresponding logic functions inside views.py.

    The Administrator Portal (admin.py)

        This file configures the backend management system. The code registers
        the Item menu model so that a system administrator can view the stored data.
        It heavily customizes the interface, adding features to display specific columns,
        search by name or description, filter by date, and can restrict a field to read-only mode.

The Core Classes: Definitions and Usages

    The system utilizes several pre-built classes from the Django framework alongside custom
    classes authored specifically for this project.

    Framework Classes (Django Core)

    models.Model: A foundational class that transforms a standard Python object into a
                    permanent SQL database table. It is inherited by the custom database blueprints to enable
                    permanent data storage.


    admin.ModelAdmin: A customization class used to manipulate the administrator interface.
                      It is inherited to add professional features like search bars and filters to the backend portal.
